<% content_for(:title, "About — Brew Finder") %>
<div class="container mt-4">
  <h1>About Brew Finder</h1>

  <p>
    Brew Finder is a Ruby on Rails application for exploring craft breweries,
    the beers they produce, and the community's reviews of them. The app was
    built for the Intro to Rails project and combines real-world data from
    three independent sources into a single relational database of seven tables.
  </p>

  <h2 class="mt-4">Data Sources</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>1. Open Brewery DB API</strong> — a public REST API returning JSON
    brewery records, including name, type, city, state/province, country, and
    GPS coordinates. The seed script queries both a general endpoint and a
    dedicated <code>by_country=canada</code> endpoint, since the general
    results skew heavily toward the United States.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>2. Craft Beers CSV</strong> — a local dataset of over 2,400 real
    beers, each with a name, style, ABV, and IBU. Unique styles are extracted
    from this file into their own <code>styles</code> table.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>3. Faker gem</strong> — generates hops, users, and reviews, since
    no reliable public dataset exists for these. Faker fills a gap the other
    two sources can't cover.
  </p>

  <h2 class="mt-4">How the Data Connects</h2>
  <p>
    The API and CSV sources don't share any common key, so at seed time each
    imported beer is linked to a randomly selected brewery already in the
    database. Beers belong to a brewery and a style. Reviews connect a user
    to a beer, forming a many-to-many relationship between users and beers.
    A second many-to-many relationship links beers and hops through a
    <code>beer_hops</code> join table.
  </p>

  <h2 class="mt-4">Entity Relationship Diagram</h2>
  <%= image_tag "erd.svg", class: "img-fluid mt-2 border rounded", alt: "Entity relationship diagram showing breweries, styles, beers, users, reviews, hops, and the beer_hops join table" %>
</div>